<HL>
   Italy's Car Sales Fell in June
</HL>
<DATE>
07/10/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP F FIA G.VOW
</CO>
<IN>
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
</IN>
<LP>
   MILAN -- Car sales in Italy fell 5.7% in June, but rose
1.8% in the first half, compared with year-earlier levels,
Anfia, the national association of car manufacturers, said.
   June car sales declined to 208,790 from 221,492, and
first-half sales increased to 1,363,061 from 1,338,535.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Domestic car makers, led by Fiat S.p.A., which produces
Fiat, Lancia and Alfa Romeo brands, accounted for 52.64% of
the domestic auto market in June and 54.43% in the first six
months. Anfia said the Fiat Uno remained the most popular on
the domestic market, with 33,231 sold in June and 244,317 in
the first six months. Fiat's Tipo took second place, with
17,315 sold in June and 126,996 in the first half.
   Among foreign brands, Volkswagen AG of West Germany led
June sales with 10,967 cars sold to the Italian market. But
Ford Motor Co., Dearborn, Mich., led the foreign brands in
the first half, when it sold 73,074 Fiesta models in Italy.
</TEXT>
