<HL>
   LEISURE &amp; ARTS:
   Timeoff: Diversions and Excursions July 10-23
</HL>
<DATE>
07/10/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A14
</SO>
<LP>
   ART
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   National Gallery of Art, Washington, D.C. -- "The
Sculpture of Indonesia" -- More than 130 objects from the
eighth through 15th centuries, the classical period of
Indonesian art. Works include Buddhist and Hindu stone
sculpture, bronzes, small figural objects of gold and silver,
and ceremonial objects. Of special interest is a life-size
Buddha, one of 504 made for the largest Buddhist temple ever
built, Borobudur. Fourth Street at Constitution Avenue NW,
through Nov. 4. The show then travels to Houston's Museum of
Fine Arts (Dec. 9, 1990-March 17, 1991); New York's
Metropolitan Museum of Art (April 21-Aug. 18, 1991); and San
Francisco's Asian Art Museum (Sept. 28, 1991-Jan. 5, 1992).
                                                                                                       

   Art Institute of Chicago: "The Chicago Skyscraper:
Selections From the Permanent Collection" -- More than 50
drawings and models document the development of the
skyscraper in the Windy City. Included are drawings of
Murphy/Jahn's Northwestern Terminal Tower (1976-87); early
prints for Burnham and Root's Rookery; and fantasy drawings
from the Chicago Architectural Club's 1983 competition to
redesign the tops of Chicago skyscrapers. Michigan Avenue at
Adams Street, July 23-Dec.31.
                                                                                                       

   IBM Gallery of Science and Art, New York: "Rediscovering
Pompeii" -- More than 200 frescoes, sculptures, vessels,
games, articles of jewelry and everyday objects from
first-century Pompeii. The exhibit also features more than 20
interactive computer programs enabling visitors to take an
electronic "walk" through the city's buildings, and see a
time-lapse sequence of the eruption of Mount Vesuvius in 79
A.D. 590 Madison Ave., July 12-Sept. 15.
                                                                                                       

   Max Protetch Gallery, New York: "Alan Sonfist: Art of the
Environment" is a 25-year overview of works by a
site-specific artist who does not inflict hostile piles of
rusting metal on squawking neighborhoods. The 20-some art
works include bronze castings of endangered oaks done for a
private estate outside Florence, and a series of collages
showing the process of his art, which often involves the
re-creation of historic landscapes. 560 Broadway, through
July 27.

   MUSIC/FESTIVAL
                                                                                                       

   Santa Fe Opera's 34th season runs through Aug. 25 and
features performances of Puccini's "La Boheme" (July 11, 20,
30, Aug. 2, 7, 14, 21 and 25); Mozart's "Cosi Fan Tutte"
(July 13, 31, Aug. 6, 11, 15 and 24); Gluck's "Orfeo ed
Euridice," with Marilyn Horne as Orfeo (July 14, 18, 27, Aug.
4, 8, 17 and 23); Strauss's "Ariadne Auf Naxos" (July 21, 25,
Aug. 3, 9, 16 and 22); and East German composer Siegfried
Matthus's "Judith," with Stephanie Sundine in the title role
(July 28, Aug. 1, 10, 18). Santa Fe Opera Theater, Santa Fe,
N.M. (505) 982-3855.
                                                                                                       

   Santa Fe Chamber Music Festival's 18th season runs through
Aug. 20. Highlights include: premiere performances of two
commissions by Pulitzer Prize-winning composers Ellen Taaffe
Zwilich and Ned Rorem; festival debut performances by the
Moscow-based Shostakovich String Quartet quartet; a piano
recital in honor of Aaron Copland's 90th birthday; and
baroque compositions played on period instruments. St.
Francis Auditorium. (505) 982-1890.
                                                                                                       

   Festival d'Ete International de Quebec: The Italian
coloratura mezzo-soprano Cecilia Bartoli makes her North
American debut with a program of Mozart and Rossini arias,
among them Sesto's aria from "La Clemenza di Tito," and the
show-stopping "Tanti Affetti" from "La Donna del Lago." The
Quebec City Symphonic Orchestra is conducted by Simon
Streatfield. Grand Theatre de Quebec, July 12. (418)
692-4540.
                                                                                                       

   Mostly Mozart Festival: Ms. Bartoli then travels to
Lincoln Center to sing one of the master's concert arias, a
tune from "Cosi fan Tutte," and "Tanti Affetti." Jean Pierre
Rampal also appears on the program with a flute concerto by
Pleyel. Gerard Schwarz conducts. July 17, 18.
   Mozart's comic one acter, "The Impresario," features
Frances Ginsberg and Sally Wolf slugging it out as rival
prima donnas and Vincent Cole as the frustrated producer.
This Tuesday and Wednesday, with the Wednesday performance
telecast on PBS. Alicia de Larrocha playing Mozart's Piano
Concerto in C major, K. 503, rounds out the program. Avery
Fisher Hall, New York. (212) 874-2424.
</TEXT>
