<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   WIC Agrees to Buy
   Media Properties
   In Western Canada
   ----
   By Gary Lamphier
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/10/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6
</SO>
<CO>
   T.WIC
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia -- Fast-growing WIC Western
International Communications Ltd. said it agreed to acquire
the media holdings of Alberta entrepreneur Dr. Charles Allard
in a cash and stock transaction valued at about 157.4 million
Canadian dollars (US$135.5 million).
   The proposed purchase would add two Alberta television
stations, as well as western Canada's Superchannel
pay-television service, and various production assets to
WIC's existing stable of radio, television, and satellite
communications operations.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "It is a major acquisition. It would make WIC one of the
largest, if not the largest, private broadcasting concern in
Canada," said Barry Gruman, a Montreal-based communications
analyst with First Marathon Securities Ltd.
   The purchase, which requires regulatory approval, would
also bolster WIC's position as western Canada's dominant
broadcaster, which it secured last year with its C$200
million purchase of broadcasting assets from Toronto's
Maclean Hunter Ltd.
   WIC agreed to acquire Edmonton, Alberta, television
station CITV, and Red Deer, Alberta, television station CKRD,
for C$90.8 million, as well as various related production and
other assets for C$19.1 million.
   WIC also agreed to acquire, for about 3.7 million new WIC
Class B nonvoting common shares, all of the shares of
Superchannel's parent, closely held Allarcom Pay Television
Ltd., that WIC didn't previously own. Under prior agreements,
WIC had acquired 21% of Allarcom's common shares.
   Mr. Allard, an Edmonton financier who built his
communications holdings after successes in real estate, holds
with his family a controlling stake in Superchannel and the
Alberta television stations.
   In Toronto Stock Exchange trading yesterday, WIC's Class B
shares closed at C$13, up 12.5 Canadian cents, giving the
stock component of the transaction an indicated value of
C$47.5 million. Mr. Allard will hold an equity stake of about
22% in WIC once the transaction closes, a WIC executive said.
Mr. Allard and his son will also become WIC directors.
   The transaction, which isn't expected to close until at
least the end of the year, would reunite WIC's
expansion-minded president and chief executive, Douglas
Holtby, with his former boss, Mr. Allard. Mr. Holtby joined
WIC about a year ago after serving as president of Mr.
Allard's broadcast operations.
   During his tenure at Allarcom, Mr. Holtby helped it score
some successes on the production side, most notably with
SCTV, a comedy program produced by Edmonton station CITV that
was subsequently picked up in the U.S. by the NBC network.
</TEXT>
