<HL>
   Defense Firm
   Gets Contract
   For Saudi Tanks
   ---
   General Dynamics' Award,
   Valued at Over $3 Billion,
   Aids Endangered Plant
   ----
   By Rick Wartzman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/10/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP CANDA GD MDEST
</CO>
<IN>
AEROSPACE (ARO)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<GV>
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
</GV>
<LP>
   General Dynamics Corp., desperate to keep open its Abrams
tank operation through overseas sales, got a big boost as the
U.S. government finalized a $3 billion-plus deal with Saudi
Arabia.
   The contract, which has long been expected, calls for
General Dynamics to supply a total of 315 next-generation M-1
tanks to the Saudis from 1993 through 1995. General Dynamics
will also supply support equipment, spare parts, training
facilities and munitions.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Along with a 550-tank co-production agreement with Egypt,
negotiated last year, General Dynamics has moved a
significant step closer to guaranteeing that its assembly
plant in Lima, Ohio, stays open. Success there for the
company would mean, in turn, that its machining shop in
Warren, Mich., also would avoid being shut. General Dynamics,
the Pentagon's No. 2 supplier and the U.S.'s only tank
manufacturer, has said it needs to produce the M-1 at a rate
of at least 360 a year to ensure that one of its two tank
assembly lines can survive.
   General Dynamics has been producing 720 M-1s a year,
accounting for nearly 10% of the St. Louis-based company's
$10 billion in sales in 1989.
   As part of the Bush administration's 1991 budget, Defense
Secretary Dick Cheney has called for ending purchases of M-1
tanks for the Army next year. But to cushion that blow and
give General Dynamics additional time to try to find other
customers, Mr. Cheney has stressed that the Pentagon's
proposal envisions filling the entire Saudi order.
   "We have no illusions about our tank business," a company
official said yesterday. "But even modest production would be
better than shutting things down entirely." General Dynamics
employs about 2,600 in Ohio and 1,200 in Michigan on the M-1
program.
   Robert Truxell, general manager of General Dynamics' Land
Systems Division, yesterday called the pact with the Saudis
"particularly important."
   "At a time of declining U.S. requirements, international
sales will play a key role in our efforts" to maintain M-1
sales in the 1990s, he said.
   Indeed, while the Saudi transaction still leaves General
Dynamics some 150 tanks short of its minimum annual
production goal -- not including any direct sales to the
Pentagon that may be restored on Capitol Hill -- the signing
of the accord could pave the way for other sales abroad. "We
could see a snowball effect," predicted Rep. Mike Oxley (R.,
Ohio).
   At present, General Dynamics is pitching the Abrams tank
to the United Arab Emirates, Sweden, Kuwait, Pakistan and
Canada. In addition, the British are expected to decide by
the end of the year if they want the M-1 to replace their
aging fleet of Chieftain tanks.
   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday,
General Dynamics shares closed up 87.5 cents at $33.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900710-0024
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900710-0024.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   House Panel Seeks
   Perjury Inquiries
   Of HUD's Ex-Chief
   ----
   By Joe Davidson
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/10/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A18
</SO>
<IN>
REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
HOUSING AND URBAN DEVELOPMENT (HUD)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The House panel investigating federal
housing corruption will ask a special prosecutor to
investigate possible acts of perjury by former housing
Secretary Samuel Pierce.
   The House employment and housing subcommittee will send a
letter of "at least 20 pages" to Arlin Adams, the special
prosecutor who was appointed this year to look into
irregularities in the Department of Housing and Urban
Development's moderate-rehabilitation rent-subsidy program.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The subcommittee will ask Mr. Adams, a retired federal
judge, to seek permission from the three-judge appellate
court panel that appointed him to expand his authority. The
subcommittee wants Mr. Adams to examine three additional
areas, the most serious of which is perjury, according to
Stuart Weisberg, the subcommittee's chief counsel.
   The letter to Mr. Adams, which Mr. Weisberg expects to be
delivered next week, will "cite the specific quotes, the
specific statements" in testimony of Mr. Pierce that the
House panel believes may be false.
   Mr. Pierce's lawyer, Paul Perito, said it is
"inconceivable" that Mr. Adams would find that the former
secretary lied. Mr. Perito added that the subcommittee's
effort is a "bold and unwarranted attempt to put the
secretary in unfavorable light with the independent counsel."
   Mr. Weisberg wouldn't give examples of possible Pierce
inconsistencies. But members of the House panel previously
have pointed to testimony from former HUD officials, who
contradicted the former secretary by indicating that Mr.
Pierce had direct involvement in awarding contracts through
political favoritism.
   In May, Attorney General Dick Thornburgh asked the special
prosecutor to expand his inquiry to include allegations of
favoritism in grants from the secretary's discretionary fund
and from an urban development program. Mr. Adams office
wouldn't say what decision, if any, has been made on the
Thornburgh request.
   Mr. Weisberg said the subcommittee won't accuse Mr. Pierce
of committing perjury, but will suggest there is reasonable
cause to believe that further investigation is warranted. "We
believe that standard has been more than met in these
instances," he said.
   He wouldn't disclose the other two areas the panel wants
the special prosecutor to examine, but Mr. Weisberg did add:
"Perjury is the one Pierce will have the most trouble with."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
